{
  "text": "Certain congenital heart defects with severe obstruction to pulmonary blood flow are almost entirely dependent on persistence of the ductus arteriosus for the maintenance of pulmonary blood flow. In those hypoxic neonates with critical pulmonary outflow tract obstruction to whom prostaglandin E1 has been administered, an immediate and persistent rise in arterial oxygen saturation has been produced. From the observations of Olley and his colleagues, this change can be ascribed to dilatation of the ductus arteriosus, with subsequent augmentation of pulmonary blood flow [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
